  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2016 by Peter Lang Verlag, <em>Forme(s) et modes d'\u00eatre / Form(s) and Modes of Being</em>, edited by Olivier Malherbe and S\u00e9bastien Richard, offers a sustained examination of Roman Ingarden's ontology. The volume has attracted modest but focused scholarly attention, with its commercial availability across multiple retail channels and appearances in open-access book listings signaling a steady, if niche, readership within Continental and analytic philosophy of ontology.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book is published within Peter Lang's established <em>Philosophie et Politique / Philosophy and Politics</em> series (ISSN 1376-0920), a bilingual imprint that has hosted comparable works on figures ranging from Hermann Lotze to questions of democratic theory and bioethics. Situating this volume within that lineage, Malherbe and Richard anchor their contribution in the phenomenological tradition, centering the work on Ingarden's complex account of form, modes of being, and ontological structure \u2014 a framework that spans the intersection of philosophy and the philosophy of physics. The bilingual French-English framing of the title itself signals an editorial ambition to reach both Francophone and Anglophone scholarly communities.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of formal citation uptake, the volume has accumulated two recorded citations, placing it in the early stages of scholarly reception. What is notable, however, is the quality and distribution of those engagements. A 2020 book chapter on meaning in Ingarden's philosophy of language, affiliated with the Universit\u00e9 Libre de Bruxelles and appearing in a volume on the history of analytic philosophy, draws directly on this work \u2014 and was co-authored by Malherbe himself, reflecting the editor's own ongoing research programme. A second, independent citation appeared in 2025 in the <em>International Journal of Philosophical Studies</em>, authored by Daniel Neumann of the University of Graz, focusing on Ingarden's theory of ideas. This latter engagement, spanning nearly a decade after initial publication and originating from a distinct national research context in Austria, suggests that the volume continues to serve as a reference point for specialists working on Ingarden's metaphysics.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's commercial presence across major retail platforms \u2014 including availability through international booksellers and digital storefronts \u2014 and its appearance in at least three open-content web listings point to a distribution footprint consistent with an actively circulating specialist title. WorldCat holdings further confirm library acquisition, supporting the volume's role as a pedagogical and research resource. Within the <em>Philosophie et Politique</em> series context, it sits alongside peer volumes addressing themes in political philosophy, ethics, and the history of ideas, benefiting from an established editorial infrastructure and a recognized venue for European philosophical scholarship.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, <em>Forme(s) et modes d'\u00eatre</em> occupies a precise but meaningful niche: a specialist contribution to Ingarden studies that has demonstrated durable relevance to researchers working at the intersection of phenomenological ontology, philosophy of language, and axiology. Its citation trajectory \u2014 with one engagement in 2020 and one as recently as 2025 \u2014 suggests slow-burn rather than immediate impact, a pattern common to focused monographic work in Continental philosophy. The volume's longevity within both commercial and academic channels indicates that it continues to meet a defined scholarly need.</p>",
